title: Who will win the 2017 Academy Award for Actress in a Supporting Role?
preds: She just won the Harvard Foundation's Artist of the Year... more credible recognition from critics and professionals. Adjust up 1%
Adjust up from 87%--> 93% for Viola Davis b/c she won a BAFTA. She cleared all major pre-Oscar awards (BAFTA, CC, GG, and SAG), making it even more probable she will win the Oscar.

No one holds a candle to Viola Davis this year in her role in Fences.  Even just from the commercials, I got shivers.  She won the Golden Globe for her role, and I see no reason to believe that she wouldn't continue on to win the Oscar.

Biases
I have not seen any of the movies. Therefore, I feel relatively removed from this awards season, as I can’t discern what is a personal favorite.
However, again I would like to acknowledge some pre-existing biases so you can take my forecast with a reasonable amount of salt: •	I have listened to 3 songs on the ‘La La Land’ soundtrack… the opening number is cute
•	As a person tired of lack of representation in Hollywood, I would personally prefer for a movie about two white people falling in love in a low-stakes situation to, y’know, not win again Here I will try to predict BEST SUPPORTING ACTRESS. I have zero familiarity with the women in this category and therefore don’t have a personal favorite. Baseline
I wanted to find a pre-Oscar award that usually accurately predicted the winner of an Oscar for my baseline. I looked at 3 big pre-Oscar awards for my baseline: the Golden Globes, the SAG awards (acting), and the Critics Choice awards. I compared their accuracy below: Start Time: 1995
Altered Start Time: 2002 I chose 1995 as my initial starting point for data as that is when the first Critic Choice awards, the youngest of the three awards, were given out.
Data (# award winners who won Oscars and this award/#years):
GG: 12/21 (57.143%)
SAG: 14/20 (70%)
CC: 13/21 (61.905%). Notice: I only counted 20 of the 21 winners for the SAG awards, b/c in 2000 Jennifer Connelly was sorted as a “lead” actress for the SAG and won the Oscar for “supporting”. Given that she was in a different category all-together, I did not count that year against the SAGs. I notice a pattern in the last 14 years that the GG, CC, and SAG got better at predicting Oscars. Before then, they were not good. Considering the youth of the CC (founded 1995) and SAG (founded 1994) pre-2002, I decided to cut off my data at 2002 instead b/c a trend had formed 2002- onwards. Data: Last 14 years  SAG: 12/14 (85.714%), GG: 8/14 (57.143%), and CC: 10/14 (71.429%) accuracy. According to this data, SAG has most accuracy at 85.714%. That will be my baseline.
Base: 85.714% for Viola Davis. BAFTA
I will update on Feb 12 after the BAFTA’s come out. If she wins that, she will have a CC, GG, SAG, and BAFTA, and that will change my prediction. Unique View
Inside view is hard for art b/c I feel like it’s more subjective. I can’t count screen-time: the awards are assigned regardless of screen time each actress has. 
I also feel like box office of a given movie won’t help. Yeah, it’s probably better for one’s chances to come from a known movie, but does your movie need to be THE blockbuster of the year to score you the win? No. Alicia Vikander won last year, and ‘The Danish Girl’ was the lowest grossing of the movies her contenders came from save for ‘Steve Jobs’. I guess the stats on an individual actor will be what awards they win and that be it for predictions in this category. Given this unique view, in addition to the SAG metric I used for my base, she also won the GG and CC. 7/8 times since 2002 an actress won those three, they’ve nabbed the Oscar. You could compare the awards in pairs also… either way you look at those numbers, winning one award increases your chances, but winning more than one helps even more. Unique view of Davis: her award history this year is indicative of future success. I’m Wrong?
Michelle Williams is looking good. She was nominated for the same things as Davis. Also, Williams won a Chicago, Santa Barbara, San Diego, New York, Toronto, and a Florida award over Davis. If it were to be anyone else, I’d shoot for her. However, her lack of showing in 3 main awards, the CC, SAG, and GG which were swept by Davis is not a good tell. If she can wring out a BAFTA, that will cause some serious stir, but she has a good showing from small critic associations.
Harris from ‘Moonlight’ looked like she nabbed two awards over Davis, but again these were small critic association ones. She’s my 3rd. Conclusions
Base: 85.714% Viola Davis. Michelle Williams adjust down (2% arbitrarily) vs. CC+SAG+GG (3% arbitrarily) win adjust up almost cancel out, but since the CC+SAG are hefty awards, her net adjustment will be up for Davis  86.714%  87%. 11% to Williams, 2% to Harris. Confidence
I feel weird putting up such a high prediction for Davis, but she’s got strong evidence. Main concern about this prediction is that it is overconfident.
